dia.com%2F348030%2Fmdh-everest-sambhar-masala-fssai-guidelines-food-safety-ethylene-oxide-fish-curry-masala-singapore-hong-kong%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Espice%20manufacturers%20use%20ethylene%20oxide%20to%20lend%20a%20long%20shelf%20life%20to%20their%20products%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIt%20is%20to%20be%20noted%20that%20the%20Food%20Safety%20and%20Standards%20of%20Authority%20India%20(FSSAI)%20doesn%E2%80%99t%20permit%20the%20use%20of%20ethylene%20oxide%20in%20any%20food%20product.%20Amid%20the%20controversy%2C%20FSSAI%20has%20announced%20the%20testing%20of%20samples%20of%20MDH%20and%20Everest%20spice%20mixes.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CSpices%20and%20spice%20blends%20like%20those%20flagged%20are%20commonly%20used%20in%20household%20cooking%20across%20multiple%20dishes.%20This%20can%20lead%20to%20chronic%2C%20persistent%20exposure%20over%20time%2C%20which%20has%20been%20linked%20to%20an%20increased%20risk%20of%20cancers%20like%20leukemia%2C%20stomach%20cancer%2C%20and%20breast%20cancer%2C%E2%80%9D%20New%20Delhi-based%20nutritionist%20Kanika%20Narang%20told%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noreferrer%20noopener%20nofollow%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Findianexpress.com%2Farticle%2Fhealth-wellness%2Fmasala-cancer-risk-fssai-test-mdh-everest-spice-mixes-hong-kong-singapore-contaminant-9285419%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3EThe%20Indian%20Express%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CUntil%20more%20rigorous%20testing%20and%20remediation%20efforts%20are%20undertaken%20by%20the%20brands%20involved%2C%20it%20is%20prudent%20for%20consumers%20to%20avoid%20the%20identified%20products%20entirely%20and%20seek%20out%20alternative%20spice%20sources%20with%20transparent%20safety%20profiles%2C%E2%80%9D%20she%20suggested.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-block-image%5C%22%3E%5Cn%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%201200px)%20100vw%2C%201200px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fen-media.thebetterindia.com%2Fuploads%2F2